<div class="header">
  <div class="header-content">
    <div class="tag">Compiled by Gemini 3.1</div>
    <h1>Lowe's (LOW)<br/>Intrinsic Value</h1>
    <p class="subtitle">A transparent, two-stage discounted cash flow valuation of Lowe's Companies, Inc. — using recent actuals, disclosed assumptions, and one final number.</p>
    <p class="date">Updated {new Date().toISOString().split('T')[0]} · Data: TTM</p>
  </div>
</div>

<div class="container">
  <!-- ═══ THE VERDICT ═══ -->
  <div class="verdict-card">
    <div class="verdict-label">Estimated Intrinsic Value Per Share</div>
    <div class="verdict-price">${roundedIV !== null ? roundedIV.toFixed(2) : 'N/A'}</div>
    <div class="verdict-vs">vs. market price of ${currentPrice !== null ? currentPrice.toFixed(2) : 'N/A'} ({marginOfSafety !== null ? marginOfSafety : 'N/A'}%)</div>
    <div class="verdict-badge" style={`background: ${verdictColor}22; color: ${verdictColor}; border: 1px solid ${verdictColor}44;`}>
      {verdictText}
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- ═══ KEY METRICS ═══ -->
  <div class="stats-row">
    <div class="stat-card">
      <div class="stat-value">{recentRev !== null ? '$' + (recentRev / 1000).toFixed(1) + 'B' : 'N/A'}</div>
      <div class="stat-label">TTM Revenue</div>
    </div>
    <div class="stat-card">
      <div class="stat-value">{fcfBase !== null ? '$' + (fcfBase / 1000).toFixed(1) + 'B' : 'N/A'}</div>
      <div class="stat-label">Free Cash Flow</div>
    </div>
    <div class="stat-card">
      <div class="stat-value">{recentEPS !== null ? '$' + recentEPS.toFixed(2) : 'N/A'}</div>
      <div class="stat-label">EPS (Diluted)</div>
    </div>
    <div class="stat-card">
      <div class="stat-value">{recentOpMargin !== null ? recentOpMargin.toFixed(1) + '%' : 'N/A'}</div>
      <div class="stat-label">Operating Margin</div>
    </div>
    <div class="stat-card">
      <div class="stat-value">{netCash !== null ? '$' + (netCash / 1000).toFixed(1) + 'B' : 'N/A'}</div>
      <div class="stat-label">Net Cash</div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- ═══ METHODOLOGY ═══ -->
  <h2>Methodology: Two-Stage DCF</h2>
  <p>We use a <strong>two-stage discounted cash flow (DCF)</strong> model — the gold standard of intrinsic valuation. No multiples, no comparables, no vibes. Just future cash flows discounted to today.</p>

  <div class="method-step">
    <div class="step-num">1</div>
    <div class="step-content">
      <h4>Start with actual Free Cash Flow</h4>
      <p>Lowe's generated <strong>${fcfBase !== null ? (fcfBase / 1000).toFixed(2) : 'N/A'} billion</strong> in free cash flow recently. This is operating cash flow minus capital expenditures. This is real cash the business produces after paying for everything, including store maintenance and capital investments.</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="method-step">
    <div class="step-num">2</div>
    <div class="step-content">
      <h4>Project FCF growth for 5 years (Phase 1)</h4>
      <p>We grow FCF at <strong>{(growthRatePhase1 * 100).toFixed(0)}% per year</strong> for 5 years. This assumes modest growth aligned with long-term macroeconomic housing trends and home improvement retail stability.</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="method-step">
    <div class="step-num">3</div>
    <div class="step-content">
      <h4>Calculate terminal value (Phase 2)</h4>
      <p>After Year 5, we assume FCF grows at <strong>{(growthRateTerminal * 100).toFixed(1)}% forever</strong>. We use the <strong>Gordon Growth Model</strong>: Terminal Value = FCF₆ ÷ (discount rate − terminal growth rate). This captures all value from Year 6 to infinity.</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="method-step">
    <div class="step-num">4</div>
    <div class="step-content">
      <h4>Discount everything to present value</h4>
      <p>All future cash flows are discounted at <strong>{(discountRate * 100).toFixed(0)}%</strong> — our required rate of return. This is the cost of equity for a large-cap retail company, built on top of the 10Y Treasury yield (4.18%) plus a reasonable equity risk premium.</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="method-step">
    <div class="step-num">5</div>
    <div class="step-content">
      <h4>Add net cash, divide by shares</h4>
      <p>Enterprise Value + Net Cash (${netCash !== null ? (netCash / 1000).toFixed(2) : 'N/A'}B) = Equity Value. We divide this by the outstanding shares ({sharesOutstanding !== null ? sharesOutstanding.toLocaleString() : 'N/A'}M) for the per-share intrinsic value.</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- ═══ THE THREE ASSUMPTIONS ═══ -->
  <h2>The Three Assumptions That Drive Everything</h2>
  <p>A DCF is only as good as its inputs. We're making exactly <strong>three</strong> judgment calls — everything else is math. Here's what we chose and why.</p>

  <div class="assumption-grid">
    <div class="assumption-card">
      <div class="label">FCF Growth Rate (Years 1-5)</div>
      <div class="value">{(growthRatePhase1 * 100).toFixed(0)}%</div>
      <div class="rationale">
        Given Lowe's mature market position in home improvement retail, massive top-line growth is unlikely. However, margin expansion, Pro-segment market share gains, and consistent store-level execution support steady, single-digit growth in free cash flow over the near term.
      </div>
    </div>
    <div class="assumption-card">
      <div class="label">Discount Rate (WACC)</div>
      <div class="value">{(discountRate * 100).toFixed(0)}%</div>
      <div class="rationale">
        10Y Treasury: 4.18%. Adding a standard equity risk premium for a stable, dividend-paying consumer cyclical company gives us a required rate of return of {(discountRate * 100).toFixed(0)}%. This reflects moderate market risk and investors' demanded return for locking up capital.
      </div>
    </div>
    <div class="assumption-card">
      <div class="label">Terminal Growth Rate</div>
      <div class="value">{(growthRateTerminal * 100).toFixed(1)}%</div>
      <div class="rationale">
        Long-term nominal GDP growth is around 2-3%. We set terminal growth at {(growthRateTerminal * 100).toFixed(1)}%, assuming Lowe's will continue to grow slightly slower than the overall economy over the long haul but will maintain its duopoly status alongside Home Depot.
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- ═══ FCF PROJECTIONS TABLE ═══ -->
