  <!-- ═══ SENSITIVITY ANALYSIS ═══ -->
  <h2>Sensitivity Analysis</h2>
  <p>Our base case uses {(growthRatePhase1 * 100).toFixed(0)}% growth and {(discountRate * 100).toFixed(0)}% discount rate. Here's what the intrinsic value looks like under different assumptions.</p>

  <div class="table-wrap">
    <table class="sensitivity-table">
      <thead>
        <tr>
          <th style="text-align:left">Discount Rate ↓ / Growth →</th>
          {sensitivityGrowth.map(g => (
            <th class={g === growthRatePhase1 ? 'current' : ''}>{(g * 100).toFixed(0)}%</th>
          ))}
        </tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody>
        {sensitivityTable.map(row => (
          <tr>
            <td>{(row.dr * 100).toFixed(0)}%</td>
            {row.values.map((v, i) => (
              <td class={row.dr === discountRate && sensitivityGrowth[i] === growthRatePhase1 ? 'current' : ''}>
                {v !== null ? '$' + v : 'N/A'}
              </td>
            ))}
          </tr>
        ))}
      </tbody>
    </table>
  </div>
  <p>The highlighted cell is our base case. Notice how sensitive the result is to the discount rate — a 1% change swings the value significantly. This is why we disclose our exact assumptions.</p>

  <!-- ═══ WHAT THE MODEL DOESN'T CAPTURE ═══ -->
  <h2>What This Model Doesn't Capture</h2>
  <p>No model is complete. Here's what a DCF inherently misses — and how it might bias our estimate.</p>

  <h3>Upside risks (our number could be too low)</h3>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Pro-Market Expansion:</strong> Lowe's successfully capturing a larger share of the resilient professional contractor market from Home Depot could accelerate revenue and margins.</li>
    <li><strong>Share Buybacks:</strong> Significant, ongoing stock repurchases artificially increase EPS and per-share value, which is not factored deeply into static share count models.</li>
    <li><strong>Macroeconomic Tailwinds:</strong> Faster-than-expected drops in mortgage rates driving a massive housing turnover boom.</li>
  </ul>

  <h3>Downside risks (our number could be too high)</h3>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Housing Market Stagnation:</strong> Prolonged high interest rates continuing to stall housing turnover and large ticket DIY projects.</li>
    <li><strong>Debt Burden:</strong> Lowe's carries significant debt. In a high-rate environment, refinancing this debt could compress net income and free cash flow.</li>
    <li><strong>Consumer Weakness:</strong> A broader economic recession reducing discretionary spending on home improvement.</li>
  </ul>

  <!-- ═══ FAQ ═══ -->
  <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
  <div class="faq">
    <details>
      <summary>Why use DCF instead of a P/E or EV/EBITDA multiple?</summary>
      <div class="faq-answer">Multiples tell you what the market <em>is</em> paying — not what a company is <em>worth</em>. A DCF forces you to state explicit assumptions about growth and risk, then lets math determine the price. It's the only valuation method that directly connects cash flow generation to value.</div>
    </details>
    <details>
      <summary>Why a {(discountRate * 100).toFixed(0)}% discount rate?</summary>
      <div class="faq-answer">The discount rate represents your required return. The 10-year Treasury yields 4.18%. Adding a historical equity risk premium gives a required rate reflecting the risk profile of Lowe's. The sensitivity table shows how values shift at higher or lower rates.</div>
    </details>
    <details>
      <summary>Is this a buy recommendation?</summary>
      <div class="faq-answer">No. This is an analytical framework for estimating intrinsic value. Whether to buy depends on your personal risk tolerance, portfolio allocation, time horizon, and conviction in the assumptions. We provide the tools and transparency — you make the decision.</div>
    </details>
  </div>

